This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE`, and .NET 10 MAUI adopts **edge-to-edge** display by default (required by Android 15+). The fix is to react to **keyboard window insets** instead.

### Solution: Handle IME insets in `MainActivity`

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme", MainLauncher = true,
          ConfigurationChanges = /* ... existing flags ... */,
          WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustNothing)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Find the MAUI content root and listen for keyboard insets
        var decorView = Window!.DecorView;
        var content = decorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var sysBarInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

            // Use whichever bottom inset is larger — keyboard or nav bar
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, sysBarInsets.Bottom);
            view.SetPadding(0, sysBarInsets.Top, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| Old approach (.NET 9) | New approach (.NET 10+) |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` told the OS to shrink the window | `WindowInsets.Type.Ime()` tells you *how tall* the keyboard is |
| Deprecated in Android API 30 | The official replacement; works edge-to-edge |

When the keyboard opens, Android delivers an insets update. The listener applies bottom padding equal to the keyboard height, pushing your input bar up. When it closes, the padding reverts to just the navigation bar height.

### XAML side — no changes needed

A standard chat layout like this just works:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" Command="{Binding SendCommand}" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

The `Auto`-row entry bar sits at the bottom; the padding shift moves it above the keyboard automatically.
